- "highest peak of success" refers to the maximum average prediction accuracy;
- "versions of the models" refers to different versions of the models identified by `model_id` and `version_number`;
- "average accuracy of their predictions" is calculated by dividing the sum of prediction accuracies by the number of predictions.

- "Flowers" refers to the models in the `models` table;
- "Most recent bloom" refers to the most recent version of each model, determined by the highest `version_id` in the `model_versions` table;
- "How well they have blossomed" refers to the average accuracy of the models, calculated from the `model_evaluations` table.

- "blooms of models" refers to the names of the models in the `models` table;
- "average essence of importance" refers to the average importance score of the features as determined by model training;
- "threshold of 0.1" means that only models with an average feature importance greater than 0.1 are considered.

- 'Training accuracy' refers to the performance of the model during the training phase;
- 'Evaluation accuracy' refers to the performance of the model during the evaluation phase;
- 'Dataset sharing' indicates how many users have access to the dataset used for training;
- 'Model version' refers to the specific iteration of the model.

- 1 MB = 1048576 bytes;
- 'Private' datasets are those where `is_public` is 0;
- 'View' sharing type allows users to view but not edit the dataset.

- The term "average prediction accuracy" refers to the mean accuracy of all predictions made by a model;
- "Total datasets used" indicates the number of unique datasets that a model has processed;
- The results are ordered to highlight the models with the best performance first.

- "gardeners" refers to users who have created models;
- "tended to more than one plant" refers to having created more than one model;
- "peeked at or pruned their garden" refers to having viewed or edited the models;
- "average time they spent nurturing each plant" refers to the average training duration of the models.

- Non-target features are features that are not the primary outcome or label in a machine learning model;
- Feature importance is a metric that indicates the relative importance of a feature in the model's predictions;
- The sum of non-target feature importance can be seen as a measure of the model's reliance on input features, excluding the target feature.

- "Top 3 models with the highest average performance" refers to the models with the highest average accuracy scores across all their evaluations;
- "Average performance" is calculated as the average accuracy score for each model;
- "Evaluations" include multiple assessments of each model's performance.
